descript.abstract: The Alberta Vegetation Inventory (AVI) is a photo-based digital inventory developed to identify the type, extent and conditions of vegetation, where it exists and what changes are occurring. This dataset consolidates all available AVI into a single feature class, with a set of extended (derived) attributes (AVIE).
descript.purpose: AVI provides detailed information to assist in the decision-making process for forest management planning, wildfire management, wildlife habitat classification and integrated resource management activities. AVI standards were developed to ensure data consistency. This dataset is a compilation of original Crown, FMA holder and other AVI datasets collected between 1987 and 2010. A variety of standards was used to collect the original data. This dataset is considered to be valid for use at a scale of approximately 1:20 000.
descript.supplinf: This dataset is for INTERNAL ESRD USE ONLY. Four main fields have been added to the database (in addition to those required under the AVI 2.1.1 standards): PHOTO_YR (year of photography); ARIS (the ARIS opening number for cutblocks); DIST_PTRN (overstory canopy pattern distribution) and LID_UND (LiDAR detected understory). Every effort was made to populate all additional fields, but some information will be missing on older datasets. AVIE has a number of derived attributes which users may find useful, including: Natural Subregion (NSR1994, NSR2005) for the old 1994 version as well as the 2005 (current) version Forest Cover Classification (FC_DOM, FC_SUBDOM, FC_COMPLEX) Percentage of each species for both overstorey and understorey species Percent conifer and percent deciduous (PCT_CONIF, PCT_DECID, UPCT_CONIF, UPCT_DECID) Cover Group (COVGRP, UCOVGRP) Seral Stage (SERAL_STGE) Seral Group (SERAL_GRP) Base 10 Strata (B10STRATA, B10CODE, UB10STRATA, UB10CODE) Area in hectares based on the native UTM Zone (UTM_HA) Provincial average coniferous, deciduous and total volume per hectare (CONIF_VOL_HA, DECID_VOL_HA, TOT_VOL_HA) Definitions for these attributes can be found under the Attributes tab. Users must be aware and understand that this dataset has been processed and may vary spatially from the original datasets. Vertex density was thinned, gaps and overlaps were removed and slivers were eliminated. Some shifting in the positioning of the linework may have occurred. The geometry has been checked and repaired. The horizontal accuracy of the original AVI data is +/- 20 meters. This dataset has not been updated to reflect post-inventory disturbance. To determine the currency of the data, refer to the PHOTO_YR field.

procstep.procdesc: tag_EDGE_FILL Because of differences in the ATS used to define administrative units, some gaps occur between neighbouring AVI areas. These gaps vary in size from less than 1 meter to over 20 meters. In order to provide continuity of AVI coverage an edge filling process was implemented to extend existing AVI data to span these gaps. The process used involved inspecting the last segment of the AVI polygon boundaries that bordered a gap area. The angle of this last segment was used to project the boundary arc to span the gap and intersect the neighbouring AVI boundary.

procstep.procdesc: tag_COVER_GROUP The Cover Group is derived from the AVI tree species and tree species percentage information. The Cover Group value is calculated for both the primary layer and the secondary layer if one exists (understory or horizontal stands). Cover Group reflects the percentage of coniferous and deciduous species that are contained in a particular stand layer. The percentages are to the nearest 10% based on crown closure. The following rules are used in calculating values: Percent Deciduous greater than 80% - D Percent Deciduous greater than 50% and percent Coniferous less than 80% - DC Percent Deciduous less greater than 20% and percent Coniferous less than 50% - CD (Note that if using the above rule a stand is classified as CD then the leading species is checked and if it is a Deciduous species the classification is modified to DC) Percent Deciduous less than 20% and percent Coniferous > 0% - C

procstep.procdesc: tag_SERAL_STAGE The Seral Stage is calculated from based on tree species composition, stand age, and Natural Sub-region. Species composition and stand age is determined from the AVI attributes. The Natural Sub-regions are calculated by intersecting the polygon with the 2005 Natural Sub-regions dataset. Only treed or harvested layers are used when calculating Seral Stage. The process begins with the stratification of the layer into its deciduous-coniferous Cover Group. This Cover Group is modified using the leading tree species for the layer. For example, the cover group C-Fd represents a coniferous stand with Douglas fir as the leading species. The exact rules for these classifications can be found in the application source code. The stand age for a layer is calculated using the current calendar year and the origin of the layer taken from the AVI. Through a series of conditional statements each cover group is evaluated by age and placed into an appropriate Seral Stage. The Seral Group for the layer is calculated by concatenating the Cover Group type to the Seral Stage attribute minus the leading species information.

procstep.procdesc: tag_NSR The dataset was intersected with the 2005 Natural Subregion polygons. An analysis of each intersecting area was performed and the Natural Suregion with the largest intersecting area was assigned to the polygon.

procstep.procdesc: tag_FOREST_COVER Forest Cover is derived from the AVI attributes and represents the Landcover or Landuse for the polygon. In general Landcover is determined by the vegetation and moisture regime of the layer. Where a layer is treed then the percentages of species is evaluated to calculate the Landcover. The thresholds of percentages that determine a particular Landcover vary and you must consult the Forest Cover application to determine specific calculations. Where a stand has associated Landuse AVI information then the Forest Cover will reflect this use. For example if a layer is AII it Forest Cover has a land use of Plant Sites/Sewage Lagoons.
